          <!-- START 1st section -->
          <hr>
          <p>A snow and weather study plot usually contains the following equipment:<\/p>
          <ul>
            <li>Instrument shelter for housing thermometers (height adjustable)<\/li>
            <li>Maximum thermometer<\/li>
            <li>Minimum thermometer<\/li>
            <li>One or more snow boards with 1 m (&sim;3 ft) rods and base plate with minimum dimensions of 40 cm x 40 cm (&sim;15
              in) and appropriate labels (<a href=\"#figure1-3Accordion\">Figure 1.3<\/a>)<\/li>
            <li>Snow stake, depth marker (graduated in cm (in))<\/li>
            <li>Ruler (graduated in cm (in))<\/li>
            <li>Snow sampling tube and weighing scale (graduated in
              grams or water equivalent), or precipitation gauge<\/li>
            <li>Large putty knife or plate for cutting snow samples<\/li>
            <li>Field book and pencil (water resistant paper)<\/li>
          <\/ul>
          <p>The following additional equipment is useful:<\/p>
          <ul>
            <li>Hygrothermograph located in an instrument shelter (<a href=\"#figure1-3Accordion\">Figure 1.3<\/a>)<\/li>
            <li>Recording precipitation gauge or rain gauge (<a href=\"#figure1-4Accordion\">Figure 1.4<\/a>)<\/li>
            <li>Additional snow boards<\/li>
            <li>First section of a Ram penetrometer<\/li>
            <li>Barograph (in the office) or barometer\/altimeter<\/li>
            <li>Anemometer at a separate wind station with radio or
              cable link to a recording instrument (<a href=\"#figured-4Accordion\">Figure D.4<\/a>)<\/li>
            <li>Box (shelter) for the equipment<\/li>
            <li>Small broom<\/li>
            <li>Snow shovel<\/li>
          <\/ul>
